- Procuring REsources:
  - While developing the project manager might find resources that aren't available within the organization. In that case, the project manager will need to obtain those resources, and this is known as procurement.

  - While a project manger discovers that the project needs resources that are unavailable, the first decision that must be made is whether the project should build or buy those resources. Building and buying both come with their own pros and cons, as well as other factors that must be considered in the decision.

- Building Resources:
  - Building the resource means that the project must commit the time and effor t necessary to complete the resource.
    - Pros: Deliverables can usually be customized to the project's needs
    - Cons: Will almost certainly increase the length tof the schedule

  - Before deciding to build the resource, the project manager must determine if the organization even has the expertise needed to complete the resource successfully. If the expertise is available, the project manager must investigate if the personnel are available within the right timeframe to complete the work. In many ways, managing the development of the resources is often a small project in and of itself.

- Buy Resources:
  - Buying the resource can seem simpler. When the project finally decides to buy a resource, the procurement process should be used.
    - Pros: Usually be available immediately, so the schedule is not impacted in the short term.
    - Cons: Might mean it will be difficult to modify the product based on the project's requirement. If time and expense to modify the resource become extensive, buying resource can sometimes be more costly.

  - If the resource is a person, then the only decision might be to obtain the necessary expertise from outside the organization, such as through contractors or vendors.

- Resource Contracts:
  - While there are many types of contracts, there are two that are often used during procurement:
    - Fixed bid contracts: Occurs when the vendor provides a single dollar quote for the cost of the resource. The advantage of this method is that the costs are known immediately so they can be worked into the project budget.
    - Time and materials contracts: Occurs when te vendor bills the project for the cost of the materials, and their actual time spent creating the resource, plus an additional markup (usually a percentage fo the total cost). This type of contract is sometimes the only choice if the resource requires greater customization.

  - Depending on the resource needed, the contract might be for time only, when only people resources are needed, or for materials only. The risk with a time and materials contract is that the cost is a variable - the exact cost will not be known to the project to at the time the budget is being prepared.
